# Whitelist for debride dead-code detection.
#
# Each entry below is a method name debride flags as dead, but we know is
# actually used through a Rails convention or framework mechanism that
# debride can't see. Every entry must have a comment explaining why.
#
# ⚠️  ADDING TO THIS FILE IS AN ANTI-PATTERN.
#
# Before adding an entry, first try:
#   1. Delete the method. Debride flagged it for a reason — if nothing calls
#      it, the method is dead code. Deleting is almost always the right fix.
#   2. Delete any test that exists *only* to exercise the method. A test that
#      pins a speculative capability ("value object supports hash-key use")
#      is still YAGNI if no production code uses that capability.
#   3. If it's genuinely called via a Rails convention / framework mechanism
#      debride can't trace (ActiveRecord reader, route action, lifecycle
#      hook), then and only then whitelist it with a comment showing the
#      implicit call site.
#
# Every new entry is developer-friction debt: reviewers must re-verify the
# justification, and it becomes a landing spot for future drift. Start from
# "delete the code" before reaching for "silence the linter."
#
# NOTE: the repo currently exceeds 50 findings even with `--rails`, so the
# code_quality:debride rake task uses a RATCHET approach: it records a
# baseline count in the task itself and fails only if the count increases.
# This whitelist is for *categories* we want to permanently suppress so
# the ratchet reflects true regressions rather than Rails noise.
#
# Format: one bare method name per line. Hash/octothorpe lines are comments.
# See: https://github.com/seattlerb/debride#whitelist

